To put it another way, language is a powerful influence on human mind. Through it, we are able to share our thoughts, emotions, and experiences with others, and it also helps form our worldview. Studies have demonstrated that the language we use may affect our ability to perceive, remember, and make choices. The study of linguistic relativity, often known as the Whorfian hypothesis, is one example of research that shows how language influences mind. According to this theory, the language we use affects our thoughts and the way we see the world. The work on color perception by Eleanor Rosch and her colleagues in the 1970s is a well-known example of research that lends credence to this theory. They discovered that compared to speakers of certain indigenous languages, whose languages include vocabulary for many more shades of blue and green, English speakers had a more difficult time differentiating between hues of the same hue. This provides evidence that the language we use affects how we interpret and conceptualize color. Overall, studies have revealed that language is an important factor in forming human mind. The language we use influences our thoughts, ideas, and worldview. One way in which language influences how we think is shown by the field of linguistic relativity, and more specifically by Eleanor Rosch's research on how color is seen. 